:"1182年","1180":"1180年","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"苏格兰阿吉爾可萊尼尼希","Argyll, Scotland":"苏格兰阿吉爾","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"英国苏格兰","lifeSummary":"当Dugald \"Duncan\" Campbell III Laird Craignish于1199年出生在苏格兰阿吉爾时，他的父亲Sir Dugald Duncan Campbell IInd of Craignish17岁，母亲Bridget MacBane20岁。他于大约1220年与Miss McSween在苏格兰阿吉爾结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他去世于1250年享年51岁。"},"hr":{"1199–1250":"1199.–1250.","1200–Female":"1200–preminula","1220–Male":"1220–preminuo","1225–Male":"1225–preminuo","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–preminula","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199.","Abt 1220":"oko 1220.","1220":"1220","about 1225":"oko 1225.","1250":"1250.","about 1220":"oko 1220.","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Škotska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Zesnulá","1220–Male":"1220–Zesnulý","1225–Male":"1225–Zesnulý","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Zesnulá","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"okolo 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"okolo 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"okolo 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Afdød","1220–Male":"1220–Afdød","1225–Male":"1225–Afdød","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Afdød","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"omkring 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"omkring 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"omkring 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Skotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Skotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Overleden","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1225–Male":"1225–Overleden","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"circa 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"circa 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"circa 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Schotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Schotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"about 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"about 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"about 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Dugald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall .  The final <i>-d</i> is due to a mishearing of the Gaelic form, in which the final <i>-ll</i> sounds like <i>-ld</i> to English ears."],"variants":[{"name":"Dougal","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall ."]},{"name":"Dubhghall","meanings":["Gaelic: from <i>dubh</i> ‘black, dark’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was a byname applied to Danes, in contrast to the fairer Norwegians and Icelanders (  compare  Fionnghall  )."]}]},{"name":"\"Duncan\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dugald \"Duncan\" Campbell III Laird Craignish was born in 1199, in Argyll, Scotland, his father, Sir Dugald Duncan Campbell IInd of Craignish, was 17 and his mother, Bridget MacBane, was 20. He married Miss McSween about 1220, in Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1250, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Abt 1220":"noin 1220","1220":"1220","about 1225":"noin 1225","1250":"1250","about 1220":"noin 1220","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Craignish, Argyll, Scotland":"Craignish, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1200–Female":"